-- ICICI Bank, Bajaj Auto, Tata Motors, Grasim, Arvind: India Equity Preview
-- Rajhkumar K Shaaw
-- 2010-08-02T03:02:38Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-08-02/icici-bank-bajaj-auto-tata-motors-grasim-arvind-india-equity-preview.html

          
          
             The following companies may have
 unusual  price changes in India  trading . Stock symbols are in
parentheses and share prices are as of the  last close .  
 The Bombay Stock Exchange’s Sensitive Index, or  Sensex ,
fell 123.71, or 0.7 percent, to 17,868.29. The S&P CNX  Nifty 
Index on the National Stock Exchange lost 0.8 percent to
5,367.60. The  BSE 200 Index  retreated 0.5 percent to 2,281.63.
The  SGX S&P CNX Nifty Index futures  for August delivery
increased 0.7 to 5409 at 10:41 a.m. in Singapore.  
 Motorcycle Makers:  Bajaj Auto Ltd.  (BJAUT IN), India’s
second-largest motorcycle maker, said its total sales of
motorcycles and three-wheelers climbed 65 percent to a record
318,415 units in July. Motorcycle sales advanced 66 percent to
279,781 units, it said in an e-mailed statement.  TVS Motor Co. 
(TVSL IN), India’s third-largest motorcycle maker, said its
total two-wheeler sales jumped 35 percent last month, while
motorcycle sales gained 42 percent. Bajaj Auto lost 0.3 percent
to 2,688 rupees, while TVS Motor gained 1.9 percent to 139.1
rupees.  
 Arvind Ltd.  (ARVND IN): The maker of cotton textiles was
raised to “outperform” from “underperform” by  Preeti Priyamvada , an analyst at Batlivala & Karani Securities, with a
share-price estimate of 36 rupees. The stock rose 2.2 percent to
34.65 rupees.  
 Bharat Petroleum Corp.  (BPCL IN) and  Indian Oil Corp.  (IOCL
IN): The state-owned refiner was cut to “neutral” from “buy”
by Goldman Sachs Group Inc. analysts led by  Nilesh Banerjee . The
analysts cut the share-price estimate for Bharat Petroleum by
8.7 percent to 685 rupees and lowered the forecast for shares of
Indian Oil by 7 percent to 400 rupees. Bharat gained 0.4 percent
to 641.55 rupees. Indian Oil advanced 2 percent to 362 rupees.  
 Cairn India Ltd  (CAIR IN): The operator of the nation’s
biggest oilfield on land was raised to “buy” from “sell” by
Goldman Sachs analysts led by  Banerjee . The analysts raised
their share-price estimate to 7.2 percent to 370 rupees. The
shares were little changed at 334.35 rupees.  
 Dr. Reddy’s Laboratories Ltd.  (DRRD IN): The drugmaker
plans to enter the Japanese market by the end of this year and
is seeking partners, the Financial Express reported, citing Vice
Chairman  G.V. Prasad . The stock fell 1.7 percent to 1354.6
rupees.  
 Grasim Industries Ltd.  (GRASIM IN): The maker of viscose
staple fiber that’s used to make tires and textiles, reported
fiscal first-quarter profit fell 47 percent to 5.75 billion
rupees ($124 million), from 10.8 billion rupees a year earlier,
in a statement to the Bombay Stock Exchange. The stock lost 0.8
percent to 1,834.05 rupees.  
 ICICI Bank Ltd.  (ICICIBC IN): India’s second-biggest lender
reported first-quarter profit rose 17 percent to 10.3 billion
rupees as it cut provisions and increased fee income. Profit
matched the 10.3 billion rupee average of 18 analyst estimates
compiled by Bloomberg.  
 Separately, the lender was raised to “outperform” from
“neutral” by Credit Suisse Group AG analysts  Ashish Gupta  and
 Deepak Ramineedi , who raised their earnings-per-share forecasts
citing lower credit costs. The analysts raised their share-price
estimate for ICICI Bank to 1,079 rupees from 826 rupees. The
stock dropped 2.6 percent to 904.9 rupees.  
 Indian Oil  (IOCL IN): The nation’s largest state-owned
refiner raised the price for jet fuel for domestic airlines by
2.7 percent in New Delhi and Mumbai. Kingfisher Airlines Ltd.
(KAIR IN) rose 3.2 percent to 52.95 rupees, SpiceJet Ltd. (SJET
IN) gained 5.9 percent to 62.4 rupees and Jet Airways (India)
Ltd. (JETIN IN) advanced 2.1 percent to 681 rupees.  
 Indiabulls Real Estate Ltd.  (IBREL IN): Indiabulls
Infratech Ltd. paid 4.74 billion rupees for the Podar Mills
(Process House) land in central Mumbai, National Textile Corp.,
or NTC, said in a statement. The amount was 90 percent more than
the reserve price for the land. Indiabulls Infratech The stock
fell 1.3 percent to 163.75 rupees.  
 Jet Airways (India) Ltd.  (JETIN IN): The nation’s largest
airline has no plans to restructure any debt because it mostly
has long-term, low-interest loans for aircraft purchases, the
Business Standard reported, citing a senior company executive it
didn’t identify. The stock rose 2.1 percent to 681 rupees.  
 NTPC Ltd.  (NATP IN): Asia’s second-largest power producer
may be able to start work on delayed projects because the
government plans to amend its gas supply policy to allow state-
owned companies to start projects before securing supplies, the
Economic Times reported, citing a government official it didn’t
identify. The stock declined 0.4 percent to 198.75 rupees.  
 Oil India Ltd.  (OINL IN): The nation’s second-biggest
state-run explorer was cut to “hold” from “buy” by BNP
Paribas analysts  Amit Shah  and  Sriram Ramesh , who said
valuations are “stretched” after a recent rally in the shares.
The analysts raised their share-price forecast for Oil India to
1,450 rupees from 1,280 rupees. The stock gained 2.3 percent to
1,409.65 rupees.  
 Reliance Industries Ltd.  (RIL IN): The government has
decided to divert gas supplies from Oil and Natural Gas Corp.’s
(ONGC IN) western offshore field to supply customers of Reliance
Industries, including Tata Power Co. (TPWR IN) and Deepak
Fertilizers & Petrochemicals Corp. (DFPC IN), the Hindu Business
Line reported, citing Petroleum Secretary  S. Sundareshan .
Reliance fell 0.1 percent to 1,009.65 rupees. Oil & Natural Gas
dropped 0.5 percent to 1,240.7 rupees. Tata Power lost 0.6
percent to 1,320.95 rupees. Deepak slid 0.4 percent to 146.65
rupees.  
 Religare Enterprises Ltd.  (RELG IN): The financial services
firm controlled by billionaire brothers Malvinder and Shivinder
 Mohan Singh  said it will raise 20 billion rupees by issuing
capital, without giving details, in a statement to the Bombay
Stock Exchange. The stock fell 0.5 percent to 417.7 rupees.  
 Steel Authority of India Ltd . (SAIL IN): The nation’s
second-biggest producer plans to sell a 5 percent stake and the
government will sell an equal share in a follow-on public offer,
the company said in an advertisement in the Economic Times today.
Banks interested in managing the sale have until Aug. 23, 5:30
p.m. local time to submit bids, it said. The stock decreased 0.5
percent to 204 rupees.  
 Tata Global Beverages Ltd.  (TGBL IN): The tea and coffee
producer was cut to “equal-weight” from “overweight” by
Morgan Stanley analysts led by  Hozefa Topiwalla , who cited
increased competition in its domestic business, higher product
development expenses, a sharp increase in coffee prices, “sub-
economic returns” on its cash holdings and the stock’s
valuation. The analysts raised their share-price estimate for
Tata Global Beverages to 105 rupees from 104.70 rupees. The
stock declined 0.5 percent to 116.05 rupees.  
 Tata Motors Ltd.  (TTMT IN): India’s biggest truck maker
reported sales climbed 41 percent in July to 67,799 vehicles in
an e-mailed statement. The stock fell 2.4 percent to 846.35
rupees.  
 Titan Industries Ltd.  (TTAN IN): The watchmaker was
downgraded to “hold” from “buy” by  Abhijeet Kundu , an
analyst at Antique Stock Broking, with a share-price estimate of
2,929 rupees. The stock fell 0.2 percent to 2,805.8 rupees.  
